Nevertheless, I'm still hopeful that as more index funds are launched it will get included, and that we can eventually solve liquidity issues in more capital efficient ways for tokens like GLYPH that represent collections with < 1k (high value) NFTs.

On a personal note, GLYPH was always one of my favorite tokens, but with NFTX's pivot to automated inventory/liquidity (as opposed to purely focussing on index funds) it is less relevant, as it tends to get very little turnover.

We plan to sell the ETH from it for USDC, but to hang onto the GLYPH for now.

More info here: https://t.co/nzuOq5it2J

We will be withdrawing most of the GLYPH/ETH liquidity this week as part of XIP-20 to set aside USDC.

The vault & token will still technically be live, but since the NFTX Dao supplies 99% of liquidity for it, it will become quite illiquid.

Just a heads up for any holders.
